<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910910-0027</DOCNO><DOCID>910910-0027.</DOCID><HL>   Business Brief -- Caterpillar Inc.:   UAW Members Authorize   Strike at Firm, if Needed</HL><DATE>09/10/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C15</SO><CO>   CAT LABOR</CO><MS>INDUSTRIAL (IDU)</MS><IN>HEAVY MACHINERY, FARM EQUIPMENT (MAC)</IN><NS>LABOR, PERSONNEL ISSUES, TRENDS, MANAGEMENT TECHNIQUES (LAB)</NS><RE>ILLINOIS (IL)MISSOURI (MO)NORTH AMERICA (NME)UNITED STATES (US)</RE><LP>   Members of the United Auto Workers union have authorized astrike, if one proves necessary, against Caterpillar Inc. asa September 30 contract-expiration date nears.   In a statement, Bill Casstevens, UAW secretary, also urgedCaterpillar management to agree on a mutually acceptableneutral location to begin central negotiations.</LP><TEXT>   The two sides haven't been able to agree on where to holdthe talks. Caterpillar wants to negotiate in its base ofPeoria, Ill., while the UAW prefers a &quot;neutral site&quot; such asSt. Louis, where the last two contracts were negotiated.   According to the UAW, union members voted by a margin ofover 95% to authorize a strike, as part of informationalmeetings held over the weekend. In 1982, the union had aseven-month strike against the company.   Caterpillar has said it needs a contract that will keepwages and benefits in line and set more flexible work rulesin its plants. The contract covers some 17,000 workers.</TEXT></DOC>